<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-456-282  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 456 282.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  July 24 1989 v23 n30 p100(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Antivirus legislation proposed.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Betts, Mitch.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The House Subcommittee on Telecommunications and Finance iscooperating with the computer software and services industry groupAdapso to draft legislation that would amend the 1986 ComputerFraud and Abuse Act to cover computer viruses.andP;  The computer-abuselaw now covers unauthorized access to federal computers.andO;Proponents of anti-virus legislation are urging Congress to betterdefine the word 'access,' specifically include 'computer programtampering' and add the concept that the disruption of computersystems is harmful.andP;  The General Accounting Office has endorsedthe concept of an anti-virus law, but university officials andothers caution that the legislation should not discriminateagainst students or restrict the free flow of data over researchnetworks.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of 1986 (amendments).andO;Topic:     United States. Congress. House. Subcommittee on Telecommunicationsand FinanceComputersComputer virusesData SecurityLegal IssuesComputer Crime.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>